metadata.name: Less Mess #66
metadata.description:
When observing the universe we can see both order and chaos, "Less Mess" is the relationship between those two forces. Randomness and order are everywhere, in each iteration of nature we can see both forces taking place. Each matter observed by us is made from ordered atoms, but each matter in its base is random and unique.

This work evolved from a simple grid. While it started as a very ordered grid, I pushed as hard as possible to make it messy and randomly beautiful. After applying a lot of mess, it becomes very busy and the order was gone. When the mess was all over the place, I started to reduce it, step by step, to bring the harmony back.

The best results are from 1000x1000 and above.

This work was created using p5.js and ‚ù§

Instagram: @asaf_slook

metadata.name: Shattered Obelisks #18
metadata.description:
Shattered Obelisks began as a work that is dedicated to my habit of mindlessly drawing on paper when I am stressed, depressed or immersed in difficult thoughts.

Like a patient undergoing psychotherapy and piecing together the causes of unconscious fears and anxieties, I and my artwork have assembled ourselves into something shaped, found order in the chaos and separated it from the external noise.

It took 3 months of continuous, obsessive work. I have developed a huge library, designed for hand-like drawing. The functionality of this library is four times larger than what is shown in this drop.

I plan to put this library out into the public domain when I deem it complete, and hope that it will help someone express themselves through the creative process as much as it helped for me.

In case you've encountered a problem with inverted colours, try changing browser or disabling extensions. This problem only occurred once during testing on a massive amount of devices and was resolved by disabling extensions.

IMPORTANT NOTES BLOCK:

NOTE 1: This artwork should be viewed at a browser scale of 100%. Reducing the scale will increase the amount of detail, but may unpredictably affect the preservation of the location of secondary objects.

NOTE 2: This work can be printed on a plotter. Click S for saving it in .SVG.
Detailed instructions and answers to possible questions can be found in the console output of the code.

NOTE 3: This drop is the first one from the series of 3. It will be used as AL ticket in next drops of this series.

metadata.name: Moving Blocks Mono #25
metadata.description:
Moving blocks formed by moving blocks.

How does it work?

Several shapes form boundaries. Within these boundaries, the moving blocks move pixels and rotate their color values from a specific color
to black.
Each shape has its own direction vector, which affects the feature-based directions and speed of the moving blocks.

Features:

- 109 colors: one from a unified color list (based on W3C SVG 1.0 color keyword names)
- 3, 5 or 7 shapes: 3 different sizes and 2 types (quads and circles)
- 1 - 3 clusters: shapes are assigned round-robin
- 10 rotation angles: from -168¬∞ to 168
- 5 grid sizes: based on Fibonacci numbers, starting with 377, block size is always 21
- Movable blocks: based on grid size (one Fibonacci number before)
- 127 directions of movement: based on 8 basic directions (up, up, left, left-up, left-down, right, right-up, right-down), limited to the 3,
  4, 8
  long combinations
- 2 behavior modes for movement distance: negative = decreasing and limited by range or shape, positive = increasing and limited by shape

Animation and feature selection are based on the deterministic prng XorShift128 seeded with the fxhash. This allows repeated playback in the
same order.

The size is fixed at 1980x1980 pixels.

The preview images are taken after 900 frames.

The animation will stop automatically at 900 frames. Press spacebar, click mouse or touch to change pausing. You can add `autopause` as
query string parameter to disable automatic pausing.

Press `c` to capture an image. Press `f` for fullscreen. Press `h` to see all options.

metadata.name: Alpinism #33
metadata.description:
‚ÄúOnly those who will risk going too far can possibly find out how far one can go.‚Äù - T.S. Eliot

---

Alpinism is a tribute to the rugged and wild landscapes that rise around us. Which may at once intrigue, impress, intimidate, and inspire.

I am captivated by the mythology of these settings. Where natural shapes appear fantastical. A ridge line drawn by pen meets sky poured out from neon gradient. Where observation is made through the lens of imagination.

Each piece begins with the concept of a mountain landscape. A number of ranges are drawn by pen in one of three styles. Within each style is a spectrum of variation that produces different drawn qualities. The backdrop may be an imagined sky, an impossible sunset, a piece of parchment. A testament to the interpreter‚Äôs memory of the scene. 

---
- Made with p5js in the White Mountains of NH July 2022
- press s to save png

metadata.name: Alleles #156
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Preliminary analysis of the information provided suggests subject may be prone to irregular episodes of disassociation and a need for constant reassurance, yet also displays the potential for a rare level of empathy and out-of-the-box thinking. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 216-222cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 64-70 years.

metadata.name: Mur #282
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Collage #186
metadata.description:
Inspired by traditional Japanese wagami design. We use the iconic patterns of our previous projects to recreate this artwork. All the patterns are generated first and then used to build the scene. 

In this project Aluan brings his delicate texture from his 'Chaos' series, Jinyao brings his beloved pattern from the 'Cloud' series and Wen brings his iconic pattern from the 'Maze'. 'Collage' is not just about mixing our style, but it is also about finding harmony among all the elements. 'Collage' is also about working together, in that we can create something that's difficult to achieve or imagine if we were working alone.

Each piece contains the patterns of all the 3 artists, each artist has a certain number of patterns with different colors. Depending which artist you get, his pattern will be shown as the primary color theme while the pattern of the other 2 artists turns into grayscale to make the primary pattern with color stand out. 

There are 7 different scenes included in this project, which are : Mountains, Waves, Lake, Hexagons, Tetrapods, Chrysanthemums and Lotus. We took great inspiration from the traditional Japanese design, and we discovered these are some of the most common elements in it. Therefore we decide to use them and reimagine them by mixing our patterns. 

The title 'Collage' doesn't only apply to the visual style, but also to the code as well. In this project we mixed p5.js and Vanilla JS. While Aluan and Jinyao work with their patterns in p5. Wen gathered the patterns and recreated the full scene in Vanilla JS.

metadata.name: Garden of Imagination #50
metadata.description:
The more a garden can sharpen all senses, the better.

The garden is one of the most artistic expressions where the five human senses are explored (sight, smell, sound, taste and touch).
It's very good to be impressed by many different colors and shapes, feel the perfume of flowers, feel the textures of plants, taste the fruits and hear the noise of leaves and birds. The more a garden manages to sharpen all the senses, the better it fulfills its role.
The challenge of this project is to provide as many sensations as possible, some you will get visually and others you will need imagination. Imagination is an essential part of this project. There are different species from different cultures that, after becoming relatives, start to interact with each other.

The Garden of Imagination is layered artwork generated from a pool of previously rendered digital assets developed for several months.

- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: Vast Difference #29
metadata.description:
This piece explores the dynamic creation of vascular cages around generative geometries. Particles are projected at a generative form, stopping when contact is made with any of the form's faces. A curve is then generated through the particles, based on the order of particle-face collision. Finally, custom tube geometry is extruded along the curve path, determining the final cage mesh. 

Interactivity: 
Panning, rotating, zooming and toggling both the internal form and particle nodes on/off.

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
o, n: hide | show particle nodes
i, v: hide | show internal form
p: screen capture

Notes:
Some renders produce noticeable delays, including possible browser alerts/warnings. This is expected behavior.
Please post your favorite 'Vast Difference' screen captures
